[b]Market Memory & Decay Oscillator [WavesUnchained][/b]

[b]What it does[/b]
Market Memory & Decay Oscillator (MMDO) scores how much statistical "memory" the current price impulse carries versus how fast that memory is decaying back toward random-walk noise. Instead of treating momentum and mean-reversion as two separate tools, it fuses four independent reads on the same lookback window into a single signed Carry/Decay axis.

[b]The four sensors[/b]
[list]
[*][b]Autocorrelation half-life[/b] — how many bars a directional impulse statistically persists before its serial correlation decays to half
[*][b]Hurst exponent approximation[/b] — separates persistent (trending) from anti-persistent (mean-reverting) regimes
[*][b]Path efficiency[/b] — net displacement vs. total distance travelled, rewarding clean directional moves over chop
[*][b]Range expansion/decay[/b] — fast-vs-slow ATR ratio, feeding both the Memory Strength and Decay Pressure sides
[/list]

[b]Reading the score[/b]
[list]
[*][b]Bullish / Bearish Carry[/b] — MMDO beyond ±25, impulse still statistically persistent
[*][b]Decay[/b] — decay pressure has overtaken memory strength; the impulse is losing coherence
[*][b]No Edge[/b] — neither carry nor decay dominates
[/list]

[b]Features[/b]
[list]
[*]Composite Memory Strength vs. Decay Pressure blend into one signed score
[*]Impulse markers on Z-score threshold breach
[*]Regime background shading (Bullish Carry / Bearish Carry / Decay)
[*]Light-theme dashboard: score, state, half-life, impulse age, Hurst, efficiency, range ratio
[*]Bullish/Bearish Carry and Impulse Decay alerts
[/list]

[b]How to use[/b]
Use MMDO to gauge whether the current impulse still has statistical legs (Carry) or is running out of memory and reverting toward noise (Decay). It is not a directional trigger by itself — pair it with a trend or structure module to time entries within the regime it reports.

